title: For Sale:  RARE Beechwood Original Czech VZ 58 with Zahal FAB add ons!
location: North End near Worthington off High, Columbus, Ohio
postcontent:
First off I need to explain that this rifle has the LOOK of an AK, but is not even close! Not even ONE part will exchange. Milled receiver made in Czechoslovakia, Chrome lined barrel, Striker fired (like a Glock), Hold open upon empty port cover, Can use stripper clips, SHORT gas fired piston, Lighter than an AK, Faster than an AK, Much Much more. It was still issued by the Czech Army up until 2011. They are still one of the more common weapons used in all the theaters we fight. They just are not the early Solid wood versions of the era just after the Warsaw Pact. In fact, the Warsaw Pact was the reason for it's creation. The Soviet Union wanted a universal cartridge (7.62 x 39), but the Czechs went on to build a "better" model of their own instead of the AK.

NOT PRESSED WOOD AND RESIN!  The Beech Wood Furniture is ORIGINAL, and is VERY hard to find intact.

If you are into collectible rifles...THIS IS THE ONE YOU WANT! It will do nothing but increase in value.

CzechPoint does not produce these rifles on a regular basis. In the past, mind you they have produced around 12 per year. This is a fact that I have in writing from CzechPoint. That alone makes this unfired rifle (except 15 - 25 rounds to zero at 25 m. after manufacture) VERY Special Indeed. The Beech was used for a Very short period of time during 1959-60? You can find pieces and parts of un-matching sets on the internet, or even re-manufactured new wood. This is the original wood used in assembly at the CzechPoint facility (in the past, they have only made around 12 per year and this was #9). I have definitely Not seen 12 Beech Wood this year! I HAVE seen a few...what does that tell you? After 1958 - 1960 the Czechs found it more cost effective and faster to use a mixture of compressed wood and resin composite (most of what you see today).

Times are changing and who knows what the future holds for these Beech Wood original rifles? The value can ONLY go up!  This hand assembled VZ stands alone in it's class. If you do the research, you will find that this rifle will out perform any AK out there. Side by side. As I said before, Not a SINGLE part is interchangeable. I suppose that the above statement is simply based upon my research on the weapon prior to me buying it.

What else makes this package so special? I am also including a "pimped out" tactical version that includes FAB furniture from Zahal in Israel as well! This includes the folding 6 position tactical Stock with all the adjustments and inside storage, both top and bottom front rails and the rubberized grip with inside storage for two 123 size batteries and something else small. There is also a NON Zahal forward grip with pop out inserts for pressure switches too. So...What it boils down to is that you can build it the way you want. I have pics of both. I am listing the photo of the original in the CzechPoint box (as it is now) with it's 2 magazines, tool kit, bayonet and OH YES! the sticker! The bipod and night sights are on the side of the CzechPoint box in the first photo. These two extra originals give the whole setup the extra special touch! I have misplaced the CD that came in the box, but I am still looking.

I purchased the Zahal "tactical accessories"  and put them onto the frame and took some photos. I felt that it took away what made the rifle "unique".  While it is already drilled and tapped for a side mount rail, I will also include a magnetic rail mount for the receiver that allows a red dot or small scope to be mounted. The rail uses a very strong magnet and supposedly returns to zero since it only has one place to rest. The jury is still out on this one. Bottom line?  You will NEVER find a package deal like this again.

Note: send me a request for more photos. I can take as many as you desire.

I am looking for a, VERY NICE 1911. ID required.
There was no choice for CzechPoint, so I chose CZ USA, the weapon is CzechPoint.

Arsenic Quick™ arsenic water test kit was designed to give the user repeatable accurate results on arenica water quality testing without sacrificing cost and time. Arsenic Water Test operating procedures The tests must be done in a ventilated area. Collect water samples and make sure its temperature is 72°F-84°F (22° - 28°C). Samples cannot be preserved with Nitric Acid or any other preservation method. Small amounts of strong acid will interfere with test results. It is best when test is done within 24 hours from the time of collection. Some water samples over 24 hours may read low. Level of Hydrogen Sulfide above 2 mg/L may interfere with the test. 1. Collect a sample into any available container, make sure it is within a required temperature range. 2. Pour 100 ml into one of the included bottles (with yellow cap). 3. Add a reagent #1. Shake well for 15 seconds 4. Add a reagent #2. Shake well for 15 seconds 5. Wait 2 minutes 6. Add a reagent #3. Shake well for 5 seconds. 7. Cap securely with a white cap, provided. Open top of the cap and slide testing strip through. Close the top with strip inside. Wait for 10 minutes. 8. Pull strip out and match the color. Disposal procedure. Discard water from the bottle down the drain that is not used for food preparation, and flush with water. Wet Zinc should be collected and disposed according to local regulations. Rinse the bottle, white cap and yellow cap with clean water. Shake off any excess water and dry white cap with soft tissue - drying white cap is especially important if you plan to run another test immediately. COOLING BURNS THE RIGHT WAY Water-Jel Burn Dressings are a gelatinized water mix designed to perform the four critical steps for burn management in one application. Because of their gelatinous nature, they seal the burn from further contamination, they cool the burn site and relieve pain by heat transfer into themselves, and the fluids on the burn site cannot soak into the dressing nor can they evaporate through them. And finally, as the burn site cools down, the dressing warms up, leaving the site covered by a warm dressing, helping to prevent hypothermia. Water-Jel Burn Dressings will absorb temperatures in excess of 2000 degrees F—extremely important when you consider that human bone carbonizes at 1400 degrees F and other dressings could melt into the site.
